TY  - JOUR
AU  - Caskey, Judson A.
T1  - Information in Equity Markets with Ambiguity-Averse Investors
PY  - 2009
Y1  - 2009/09/01
DO  - 10.1093/rfs/hhn062
JO  - The Review of Financial Studies
JA  - Rev Financ Stud
VL  - 22
IS  - 9
SP  - 3595
EP  - 3627
SN  - 0893-9454
AB  - This paper shows that persistent mispricing is consistent with a market that includes ambiguity-averse investors. In particular, ambiguity-averse investors may prefer to trade based on aggregate signals that reduce ambiguity at the cost of a loss in information. Equilibrium prices may therefore fail to impound publicly available information. While this creates profit opportunities for ambiguity-neutral investors, ambiguity-averse investors perceive that the benefit of ambiguity reduction outweighs the cost of trading against investors who have superior information. The model can explain both underreaction, such as that evident in postearnings announcement drifts and momentum, and overreaction to accounting accruals.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rfs/hhn062
ER  - 



